{"cursor":"5555","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox royalty\n| type = monarch name = Bermudo III image =Bermudo III de LeÃ³n (Ayuntamiento\n| de LeÃ³n).jpg imgw =170px caption = succession = King of LeÃ³n reign =\n| 1028–1037 coronation = predecessor = Alfonso V successor = Ferdinand I\n| spouse = Jimena SÃ¡nchez issue = Alfonso issue-link = issue-pipe = full name\n| = Bermudo AlfÃ³nsez house = Beni Alfons house-type = Dynasty father = Alfonso\n| V of LeÃ³n mother = Elvira Mendes birth_date = c. 1017 birth_place =\n| death_date = 4 September 1037 death_place = TamarÃ³n burial_place = Basilica\n| of San Isidoro later Santa MarÃ­a la Real of NÃ¡jera religion = Roman\n| Catholicism }}\n'Bermudo III' (1017 â 4 September 1037), king of LeÃ³n (1028 â 4 September 1037),\nson of Alfonso V of LeÃ³n by his wife Elvira Mendes, was the last scion of Peter\nof Cantabria to rule in the Leonese kingdom. He was called Emperor in Galicia in\n1025. [http://books.google.com/books?id=P6NCAAAAYAAJ&q=%22imperator+in+Gall-\necia%22&dq=%22imperator+in+Gallecia%22&hl=en&ei=-\nGNdTOmcFo6nsQbTpbmNCA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA\nHistoria crÃ­tica de Vizcaya y de sus fueros. ]\n\nIn 1029, Count GarcÃ­a SÃ¡nchez of Castile was about to be married to Sancha of\nLeÃ³n, the sister of Bermudo, an arrangement apparently sanctioned by the king of\nNavarre, when the count was murdered in the city of LeÃ³n. Sancho III of Navarre\nthen claimed the county of Castile in his wife's name and installed in it their\nson, Ferdinand, as the new count of Castile. The Navarrese king's policy turned\nto pure aggrandisementâsometimes ostensibly on behalf of his son and at other\ntimes simply on his own behalf. He seized the (linguistic) borderlands between\nthe Cea and the Pisuerga rivers, right above LeÃ³n capital, long a bone of\ncontention between LeÃ³n and Castile. After he had forced the marriage between\nFernando and Sancha in 1032, those lands went to Castile as part of her also\nforced dowry. In 1034, he wrested the city of LeÃ³n itself from Bermudo, who\nretreated into Galicia. By the time Sancho died in 1035, the [[Meseta\nCentral|meseta]] north of the Duero was dominated by the Pyrenean pocket kingdom\nof Navarre.\n\nHowever, for all of Sancho's diplomatic and military skill, one cannot help but\nthink that such a situation was essentially the fortuitous result of having\nyouthful opponents. Certainly the brute facts of geography and demography\nmilitated against its continuance. After his death, Bermudo III was immediately\nreceived back into LeÃ³n and soon began a campaign to recover from Castile and\nhis brother-in-law the disputed territory between the Cea and Pisuerga. But\nFerdinand defeated and personally killed Bermudo III at the Battle of TamarÃ³n\non September 4, 1037. Bernard F. Reilly, The Contest of Christian and\nMuslim Spain, 1031-1157, (Blackwell, 1995), 27. Autopsy of his remains\nshows that he may have suffered death from infantry spears or pikes, after\nfalling from his horse.\n\nSince the latter died without an heir, the kingdom of LeÃ³n now recognized Sancha\nand her husband as its rulers, and Ferdinand was anointed king in the royal city\non June 22, 1038. The dynasty of Navarre had triumphed perhaps, but the united\nrealm of LeÃ³n and Castile with its rimlands of Asturias and Galicia, had become\nthe political center of the north Iberian Christian society.\n","linknr":215,"url":"Bermudo_III_of_León","recorded":1375075539,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Bermudo_III_of_Le%C3%B3n&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Bermudo_III_of_Le%C3%B3n&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteah